{{Bahá'í sidebar}}
The '''Bahá'í Faith in Morocco''' began about 1946.<ref name="BN183">{{cite magazine | title = News of Other Lands; Geneva Bahá'í Bureau |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1946 | number = 183 | page =9 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=845}}</ref><ref name="BN327">{{cite magazine | title = Legal Recognition, Increase in Centers Reported in Morocco|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1958 | number = 327 | page =14 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=761}}</ref> In 1953 the Bahá'ís initiated a [[Ten Year Crusade]] during which a number of Bahá'ís [[pioneering (Bahá'í)|pioneered]] to various parts of Morocco—many of whom came from [[Bahá'í Faith in Egypt|Egypt]] and a few from the United States including [[Helen Elsie Austin]].<ref name="hassal-egypt">{{cite web | last = Hassall | first = Graham | title = Egypt: Baha'i history | work = Asia Pacific Bahá'í Studies: Bahá'í Communities by country | publisher = Bahá'í Online Library | date = c. 2000| url = http://bahai-library.com/asia-pacific/country%20files/egypt.htm | accessdate = 2009-05-24}}</ref><ref name="basic">{{cite book|author=Cameron, G.|author2=Momen, W.|year= 1996|title= A Basic Bahá'í Chronology|publisher= George Ronald|location=Oxford, UK|isbn= 0-85398-404-2|pages =301, 304–5, 306, 308, 328, 329, 331, 354–359, 375, 400, 435, 440–441 }}</ref> By April 1955 the first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] of [[Ceuta]] was elected.<ref name="BN300">{{cite magazine | title = First Local Spiritual Assembly of Ceuta... |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1956 | number = 300 | page =7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=281}}</ref> By January 1958 the first Bahá'í summer school was held in [[Rabat]].<ref name="BN323">{{cite magazine | title = First Bahá'í Summer Schoot...|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1958 | number = 323 | page =12 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=687}}</ref> By spring 1958 the Bahá'í population may have been 100 and there were six assemblies and a regional committee coordinated activities promulgating the religion.<ref name="BN327" /> In 1960 the first all-Moroccan local assembly was elected in [[Zaouiat Cheikh]] and most of its members were [[Berber people|Berbers]].<ref name="BN354">{{cite magazine | title = First Local Spiritual Assembly of Zaouiat Cheikh |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1960 | number = 354 | page =12 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=134}}</ref> On December 7, 1961 an article in [[Al Alam]] laments the decline of Islam and attacks the Bahá'ís.<ref name="basic" /> During the year Bahá'í homes are entered by police and literature of the religion is taken. On April 12 four Bahá'ís are arrested in Nador.<ref name="basic" /> A regional National Spiritual Assembly of North West Africa was organized which included Morocco in 1962.<ref name="notesAfrica">{{cite web | last =Hassall | first = Graham | title = This note concerns references to Africa in the Bahá'í Writings | work = Asian/Pacific Collection | publisher = Asia Pacific Bahá'í Studies | date = 2003-08-26 | url =http://bahai-library.com/asia-pacific/country%20files/africa.htm | accessdate = 2008-11-18}}</ref> In 1963 a survey of the community counted 10 Assemblies, 12 organized groups (between 1 and 9 adults) of Bahá'ís.<ref name="stats">{{cite web | url = http://bahai-library.com/handscause_statistics_1953-63&chapter=1#19 | title = The Bahá'í Faith: 1844-1963: Information Statistical and Comparative, Including the Achievements of the Ten Year International Bahá'í Teaching & Consolidation Plan 1953-1963| author = Compiled by [[Hands of the Cause]] Residing in the Holy Land | pages = 25, 83, 103, 115}}</ref> In 1963 the arrests in Morocco had gotten attention from [[Hassan II of Morocco]], US Senator [[Kenneth B. Keating]]<ref name="custodians">{{cite book |author=Rabbani, R. (Ed.) |authorlink=Rúhíyyih Khanum |year=1992 |title=The Ministry of the Custodians 1957-1963 |publisher=Bahá'í World Centre |isbn=0-85398-350-X |url=http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ministry_custodians&chapter=6#397 |pages = 414–419}}</ref> and [[Roger Nash Baldwin]], then Chairman of the [[International League for the Rights of Man]]<ref name="basic" /> and would echo in analyses of politics of Morocco for years to come.<ref name="oldnew">{{Cite book| last = Cohen, | first = Mark L.|author2=Lorna Hahn | title = Morocco: old land, new nation | publisher = Frederick A. Praeger | year = 1966 | pages = 141–146 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=FFByAAAAMAAJ&q=Bahai#search_anchor | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="WCMES">{{Cite conference | first = Bouasria | last = Abdelilah | title = The other 'Commander of the faithful': Morocco's King Mohammed VI's religious policy | booktitle = World Congress for Middle Eastern Studies | publisher = European Institute of the Mediterranean | date = | location = | url =http://wocmes.iemed.org/en/preorg-second-decade | accessdate = 2010-06-07| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100502065705/http://wocmes.iemed.org/en/preorg-second-decade| archivedate= 2 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> All Bahá'í meetings were prohibited in 1983 followed by arrests.<ref name="basic" /> This time the response emphasized the non-partisan and obedience to government principles of the religion.<ref name="smith">{{cite journal|url=http://bahai-library.com/momen_smith_developments_1957-1988|title=The Bahá'í Faith 1957-1988: A Survey of Contemporary Developments |first=Peter |last=Smith |author2=Momen, Moojan |journal=Religion |year=1989 |volume=19 |pages=63–91 |doi=10.1016/0048-721X(89)90077-8}}</ref> 1992 estimates by the US Department of State counted some 150-200 Bahá'ís.<ref name="HRP-93">{{cite web | author = U.S. State Department | title = Morocco Human Rights Practices, 1993 | publisher = The Office of Electronic Information, Bureau of Public Affair | date = January 31, 1994 | url = http://dosfan.lib.uic.edu/ERC/democracy/1993_hrp_report/93hrp_report_nea/Morocco.html | accessdate = 2010-06-07}}</ref> while 2001 through 2009 estimates mention the Bahá'í community at 350 to 400 persons.<ref name="IRF2001" /><ref name="IRF2009">{{cite web | author = U.S. State Department | title = 2009 Report on International Religious Freedom&nbsp;– Morocco | publisher = The Office of Electronic Information, Bureau of Public Affair | date = October 26, 2009 | url = https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127354.htm | accessdate = 2010-06-07}}</ref> However [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] and [[Wolfram Alpha]]<ref name="Wolfram">{{Cite encyclopedia | title = Morocco: population, capital, cities, GDP, map, flag, currency, languages, ... | encyclopedia = Wolfram Alpha | volume = Online | publisher = Wolfram&nbsp;– Alpha (curated data) | date = March 13, 2010 | url =http://www.wolframalpha.com/entities/countries/morocco/o5/jg/ko/ | accessdate = 2010-06-06}}</ref> estimated 33,000 Bahá'ís in 2005 and 2010,<ref name="ARDA-BahaiNations">{{cite web| title = Most Baha'i Nations (2010) | work = International > Regions > Northern Africa | publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2010| url =http://www.thearda.com/QL2010/QuickList_40.asp | accessdate = 2013-10-22}}</ref> the third largest religion in the country.<ref name="ARDA-Morocco">{{cite web| title = Morocco | work = International > Regions > Northern Africa| publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2010| url =http://www.thearda.com/internationalData/countries/Country_155_2.asp | accessdate = 2013-10-22}}</ref>

== Early phase ==

There is a mention of contact with a Bahá'í in Morocco in 1946 but it's unclear with division (Spanish, French, International Zone.)<ref name="BN183" /><ref name="BN327" /> In August 1947 Marie Claudet, former member of the Baha'i Assembly of Guayaquil (Ecuador) was reported in May to be en route to French Morocco.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = News of Other Lands; From Geneva News Bulletin; Morocco |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1947 | number = 198 | page =10 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1030}}</ref> In 1953 the Bahá'ís initiated a [[Ten Year Crusade]] during which a number of Bahá'ís [[pioneering (Bahá'í)|pioneered]] to various parts of Morocco—many of whom came from [[Bahá'í Faith in Egypt|Egypt]] and a few from the United States.<ref name="hassal-egypt" /><ref name="basic" /> Starting in September for the Moroccan [[International Zone]] they first to arrive were: Manu<u>ch</u>ihi Hizari, and Hurmuz Zindih. Manouchehr Hezari earned the title of [[Knights of Bahá'u'lláh|Knight of Bahá’u’lláh]] as the very first to settle in Tangier (then an international city).<ref>{{cite web | title =Manouchehr Hezari helped introduce the Faith to Morocco | work = | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of the United States | date =September 13, 2010 | url =http://www.bahai.us/2010/09/13/manouchehr-hezari-helped-introduce-the-faith-to-morocco/ | accessdate = | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20111216151637/http://www.bahai.us/2010/09/13/manouchehr-hezari-helped-introduce-the-faith-to-morocco/ | archive-date =2011-12-16 | dead-url =yes | df = }}</ref> The family stayed many years after Tangier was annexed by the Kingdom of Morocco. Manouchehr worked as an engineer and later as a station manager for Voice of America radio. Then in October more arrivals came—Dr. [[Helen Elsie Austin]]<ref>[http://bahai-library.com/writings/shoghieffendi/mbw/mbwall.html MESSAGES TO THE BAHA'I WORLD: 1950-1957, © (U.S., 1971)] page 52</ref> and Muhammad-'Ali Jalili came. In November Husayn & Nusraat Ardikani, 'Ali Akhbar & <u>Sh</u>ayistih Rafi'i, and 'Abbas Rafi'i arrived. For [[Spanish Morocco]] in October 1953 they were: Fawzi Zaynu'l-'Abidin & family, Luella McKay, John & Earleta Fleming, and Alyce Janssen.<ref name="hassal-egypt" /><ref name="basic" /><ref>{{cite book|author=The Universal House of Justice|authorlink=Universal House of Justice|year=1974|title=The Bahá’í World&nbsp;– An International Record Vol XIV 1963-1968&nbsp;– From a letter written by Luella McKay|publisher=Broadwater Press Limited|location=Welwyn Garden City, Hertfordshire, England}}</ref> Others arrived in April 1954—Richard & Evelyn Walters and Richard & Mary L. Suhm.<ref name="hassal-egypt" /> Helen Austin was teaching at [[the American School of Tangier]] from 1954 to 1957. She was a member of the regional National Assembly of North and West Africa (1953–58), and, in her lifetime, [[Local Spiritual Assemblies]] in five countries—including Morocco.<ref name="bahainews">{{Cite news | title = Standing up for justice and truth| newspaper = Bahá'í World News service | location = San Antonio, United States | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | date = 5 December 2004 | url =http://news.bahai.org/story/338 | accessdate = 2010-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Thomas | first = Richard Walter |author2=Gwnedonlyn Etter-Lewis | title = Lights of the spirit: historical portraits of Black Bahá'ís in North America| chapter =Race, Gender, and Difference: African-American Women and the Struggle for Equality | chapterurl =https://books.google.com/books?id=L2KVX4mx1xEC&lpg=PA136&pg=PA135#v=onepage&q&f=false | publisher = US Baha'i Publishing Trust | year = 2006 | pages = 135–137 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=L2KVX4mx1xEC&source=gbs_navlinks_s | isbn = 978-1-931847-26-1 }}</ref> Another American family pioneered to Morocco starting in 1956 up to 1960, one returning for a period in 1967-8.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Lee | first =Anthony A. | editor-last = Appiah| editor-first =Kwame Anthony | editor2-last = Gates | editor2-first =Henry Louis, Jr. | title =Badi G. Foster | encyclopedia =Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience | edition =Second | publisher =Oxford African American Studies Center | url = http://www.oxfordaasc.com/article/opr/t0002/e1517 | year = 2006 | accessdate = 2012-02-16}}</ref> By February 1955 there is mention of conversions from the Moroccan population.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = National News; United States Africa Teaching Committee; Africa News |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1955 | number = 288 |pages=7–8 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=109}}</ref> By April 1955 the first Local Spiritual Assembly of [[Ceuta]], an enclave of Spain in Morocco, was elected.<ref name="BN300" /> Sometime during 1956 a Roman Catholic priest lodges a complaint against the Bahá'ís of Morocco with the Moroccan Security Service.<ref name="basic" /> By January 1958 the first Bahá'í Summer School was held in Rabat.<ref name="BN323" /> By spring 1958 the Bahá'í population may have been 100 and there were six assemblies and a regional committee is coordinating activities promulgating the religion.<ref name="BN327" /> In 1960 the first all-Moroccan local assembly was elected in Zaouiat Cheikh and most of its members were [[Berber people|Berbers]].<ref name="BN354" /> A regional National Spiritual Assembly for North East is organized in 1956.<ref name="basic" /> In 1957 the first [[Tuareg people|Tuareg]] joins the religion.<ref name="basic" /> Louella McKay was another pioneer from about spring 1959 through the fall of 1963 in Spanish Morocco.<ref>{{cite magazine | title =Baha'i in the News |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1964 | number = 399 | page =11 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=825}}</ref>

A regional National Spiritual Assembly of North West Africa was organized<ref name="notesAfrica" /> in 1962-3 including the merging countries of [[French Morocco|French]], [[Spanish Morocco]] and the Moroccan [[International Zone]] centered on Tangiers.<ref name="stats" /> In 1963 a survey of the community counted 10 Assemblies, 12 organized groups of Bahá'ís and 8 isolated individuals. The assemblies were: [[Casablanca]], [[Ceuta]], [[Fes|Fez]], [[Kenitra]], [[Larache]], [[Marrakesh]], [[Meknès]], [[Nador]], [[Rabat]], [[Chellah|Sala]], [[Tetuan]] and [[Zaouiat Cheikh]].

== Growth ==

=== Persecution ===

In [[Morocco]] there were episodes of religious persecution in 1962-1963, on the basis of condemnation from [[Allal El Fassi]] when 15 Bahá'ís were arrested for their religious convictions; three were given death sentences.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Divinity School Members Protest Verdict on Baha'i| newspaper = The Harvard Crimson | publisher = | date = January 18, 1963 | url =http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1963/1/18/divinity-school-members-protest-verdict-on/| accessdate = 2010-06-07}}</ref> On December 7, 1961 an article in [[Al Alam]] laments the decline of Islam and attacks the Bahá'ís.<ref name="basic" /> During the year Bahá'í homes are entered by police and literature of the religion is taken. On April 12 four Bahá'ís are arrested in Nador.<ref name="basic" /> In September the Bahá'ís in the United States contacted [[Hassan II of Morocco]] during a visit to the United Nations.<ref name="basic" /> On October 31, fourteen Bahá'ís are arrested and are charged with rebellion, disorder, attacks on public security, being an association of criminals, and attacking religious faith.<ref name="basic" /> On 10 December the trial begins with charges of sedition. On the 14th the verdict is given—four are acquitted as they claim to be Muslims, one is acquitted through family connections, one is released on 15 years probation, five are committed to life imprisonment and three are sentenced to death.<ref name="basic" /> The sentences are appealed to the Moroccan supreme court.<ref name="custodians" /> Initially Bahá'ís did not publicize the events.<ref>The first mention in ''Bahá'í News'' of the events was in November 1962 by way of covering news in [[Le Monde]]. It was not until January 1963 that a compendium on the events was published by the Baha'is - {{cite book | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | authorlink = Bahá'í International Community | title = Freedom of Religion on Trial in Morocco: The Nador Case | publisher = Humanities & Social Sciences Online, Michigan State University | date = January 1963 | url = http://www.h-net.org/~bahai/diglib/books/A-E/B/BIC/Morocco_Case_1963.pdf}}
* {{cite magazine | title = Baha'i in the News |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1962 | number = 380 | page = 14 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=544}}
* The first significant coverage was in March 1963 {{cite magazine | title = World Center Shares Stirring Events of Moroccan Drama |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1963 | number = 384 | pages = 1–4 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=605}}</ref> On December 17, 1962 news is released among the Bahá'ís and efforts are aimed at asking for the applicability of the UN charter which condemns religious intolerance.<ref name="basic" /> On January 31 [[Roger Nash Baldwin]], then Chairman of the [[International League for the Rights of Man]], appeared before a UN sub-commission of Preventing Discrimination and Protection of Minorities and states that, as far as they knew, the Bahá'í prisoners in Morocco are the only example in recent history where members of a religions have been condemned to death solely for holding and expressing religious views regarded as heretical.<ref name="basic" /> This appeal through the UN was supported by nearly the entire body of the Harvard Divinity School.<ref>{{cite news| title =Divinity School Members Protest Verdict on Baha'i| newspaper =The Harvard Crimson | publisher = The Harvard Crimson, Inc. | date =January 18, 1963 | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1963/1/18/divinity-school-members-protest-verdict-on/ | accessdate = 2012-02-16}}</ref> There were months of diplomatic efforts; US Senator [[Kenneth B. Keating]] stated in the [[U.S. Senate]] on February 18, 1963, "How far religious freedom under the Moroccan Constitution really applies, will be revealed in the coming weeks when the appeal before the Supreme Court [of Morocco] is heard."<ref name="custodians" /> On March 31, 1963 during a visit to the United States and the United Nations, [[Hassan II of Morocco]] was interviewed on television on [[Meet the Press]] then with [[Lawrence E. Spivak]] and was asked about the treatment of Bahá'ís in his own country.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Rutstein | first = Nathan | title = From a Gnat to an Eagle: The Story of Nathan Rutstein | publisher = US Baha'i Publishing Trust | year = 2008 | page = 119 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aR2AIrHGrH4C&lpg=PA71&pg=PA119#v=onepage&q&f=false| isbn = 978-1-931847-46-9}}</ref> He addressed the audience saying that the Bahá'í Faith was not a religion and "against good order and also morals". However, on April 2 he makes a public statement that if the Supreme Court confirms the penalty of death that he would grant them a royal pardon. However, on November 23 the Supreme Court hears the appeals and reversed the decision of the lower court. On December 13 the prisoners are actually released.<ref name="basic" /> Coverage in newspapers of the day included Wisconsin,<ref>{{Cite news | title = Baha'is Protest Morocco Action | newspaper = Wisconsin State Journal | page = 21 | date = January 3, 1963 | url = http://www.newspaperarchive.com/PdfViewerTags.aspx?img=105297562&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0&fpo=False | accessdate = 2010-06-11}}</ref> Winnipeg and<ref>{{Cite news| title = Morocco to Execute 3 Bahais | newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press | page = 15 | date = 1963-12-19 | url =http://www.newspaperarchive.com/PdfViewerTags.aspx?img=42162826&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=1&currentPage=0&fpo=False | accessdate = 2010-06-11}}</ref> Lethbridge, Canada<ref>{{Cite news | title = Sentences Bahai Sect Members to Death | newspaper = Lethbridge Herald | page = 2 | date = 1963-12-13 | url = http://www.newspaperarchive.com/PdfViewerTags.aspx?img=62528732&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=1&currentPage=10&fpo=False | accessdate = 2010-06-11}}</ref> and Elyria Ohio<ref>{{Cite news| title = International Scene | newspaper = Chronicle Telegram | page = 2 | date = 1963-04-02 | url =http://www.newspaperarchive.com/PdfViewerTags.aspx?img=8577117&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=2&currentPage=10&fpo=False | accessdate = 2010-06-11}}</ref> as well as the New York Times.<ref>{{Cite news | title = various | newspaper = New York Times | pages = various | date = 1963 | url = https://query.nytimes.com/search/sitesearch?query=bahai+morocco+1963&more=date_all | accessdate = 2010-06-11}} {{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref>{{BCN|date=October 2016|reason=Search results vary over time, and aren't concrete references.}} ''[[The New Republic]]'' January 25, 1964 issue had an article by [[Roger Nash Baldwin]], founder of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] and member of the [[International League for the Rights of Man]] (an organization accredited by the UN which aims to spread civil liberties around the world).<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Baha'i in the News |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1964 | number = 400 | page = 15| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=846}}</ref> Baldwin mentions how the League, by applying public pressure on the King of Morocco helped save the lives of the Bahá'í prisoners who had been sentenced to death. Baldwin was quoted discussing the League, "All this adds up to the very tiny beginnings of a system by which the UN itself would examine and process complaints and ultimately help set up a world court of human rights."

''Morocco, Old Land, New Nation'' published in 1966<ref name="oldnew" /> discusses<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Baha'i in the News |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1966 | number = 428 | page = 19| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=475}}</ref> briefly the exploitation of the religion by a Moroccan political party, in an effort to dramatize a claim "to be the stanch defender of faith and country," and the resultant persecution and imprisonment of several young Baha'i men from Nador. Concerning the Faith, the authors write: "The attractiveness of the movement stemmed from its belief in world brotherhood (a factor in its recent appeal in certain parts of Africa), the dedication of its organizers, and the vitality of its discussions, which contrasted sharply with the small concern in Morocco with the possibility of modernizing Islam." The reactions of various Moroccan leaders, newspaper publicity, and the final reversal of the convictions are noted.

=== Development of the community ===

The first summer school of Morocco for Bahá'ís was held in Meknes, from August 31 to September 6. Over twenty participants were gathered on a farm situated in a suburb of Meknes, belonging to one of the Persian pioneers, Hossein Rowhani Ardakani. The city of Meknes, with more than seventy registered Baha'is, has the largest Bahá'í community in Morocco in 1964.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = First Summer School in Morocco |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1964 | number = 405 | page = 2| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=66}}</ref> Bahá'ís from Morocco, Tunisia, Belgium, England, Monte Carlo and the Netherlands attended a school in Périgueux, France and shared news of the progress of the religion in their countries.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Baha'i Summer School Held in Perigueux, France |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1964 | number = 405 | page = 5| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=69}}</ref> Before June 1965 [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Taráz'u'lláh Samandarí]] visited the Bahá'ís of Morocco.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Baha'i Summer School Held in Perigueux, France |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1965 | number = 411 | page = 10| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=166}}</ref> The Rabat Bahá'í community hosted the May 1–2, 1965 convention for the regional national assembly of North West Africa. All the delegates, except one, were present.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = All delegates, except one, were present... |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1965 | number = 413 | page = 3| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=195}}</ref> The three Benelux countries held their schools at a combined site at De Vechtstrom in the northern Netherlands from August 23 through 30 1965 together with 150 attendees from fifteen countries including Morocco, Tunisia, Japan, Great Britain, United States and others from Europe.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Benelux Summer School Held in De Vechtstrom, the Netherlands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1965 | number = 416 | page = 6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=246}}</ref> The second summer school of Morocco was held in Meknes, August 23 to 29, 1965 with about one hundred Bahá'ís and inquirers and for the first time a greater number of women were present than at previous schools.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Benelux Summer School Held in De Vechtstrom, the Netherlands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1965 | number = 416 | page = 8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=248}}</ref> Issam Tahan died on August 8, 1965 in London during treatment for heart problems. He was the small boy who, while his father was in prison in Morocco, chanted a prayer before the audience at the first [[Bahá'í World Congress]].<ref>{{cite magazine | title = News Briefs|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1965 | number = 417 | page = 23| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=279}}</ref> A summer school in Meknes was held August 1–7, 1966, which attracted about forty participants. Basic courses on administration and history were given, with additional lectures on special topics such as [[Bahá'í Faith and gender equality|Women and the Bahá'í Faith]], [[Bahá'í Faith and education]], and a special study of the Message of the [[Universal House of Justice]] to Bahá'í youth.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = News Briefs|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1966 | number = 429 | page = 17| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=493}}</ref> The first winter school was held in Rabat February 25–26, 1967 with twenty-five communities represented.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = First winter schoot held in Rabat... |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1966 | number = 435 | page = 8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=600}}</ref> In before fall 1967 [[Hands of the Cause]] [[William Sears (Bahá'í)|William Sears]] and [[Shu'á'u'lláh `Alá']] met with the Bahá'ís in Casablanca and the regional national assembly for a week.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = North West Africa |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1967 | number = 439 | page = 5| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=677}}</ref> The fifth national summer school was held in Meknes September 3–9, 1967, with about 70 attendees from 14 localities. A young girl from Marrakech delivered a prepared lecture on the role of women in the Baha'i Faith presenting an example of women as efficient and active participants.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Moroccan School Welcomes Seventy Participants |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1967 | number = 440 | page = 9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=701}}</ref> The annual convention for the regional assembly was held in Rabat in April 1968.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Convention of North West Africa |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1968 | number = 449 | page = 13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=173}}</ref> An international conference was held in Madrid in early April, 1969, organized by the National Youth Committee of Spain with over thirty young Baha'is attendees, representing Austria, England, France, Italy, Morocco, Portugal, Spain, and Switzerland.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Madrid Site of First European Youth Conference |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1969 | number = 461 | page = 9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=377}}</ref> In 1968 a Bahá'í was arrested and would spend four years in prison.<ref name="BN494">{{cite magazine | title = A Prisoner for his Faith Gains Freedom |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1972 | number = 494 | page = 9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=81}}</ref> The 1970 French summer school, held at Annecy/Sevrier from August 30 to September 8, had attendees of 150 persons from Germany, England, Belgium, Denmark, India, Luxembourg, Dominica, Morocco, Sweden, Switzerland, Tunisia.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = French School Hosts Twelve Countries |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1970 | number = 466 | page = 15| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=487}}</ref> However, in 1970 the annual Convention did not take place due to the situation in Morocco. The elections were accomplished through mail correspondence.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = North West Africa |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1970 | number = 475 | page = 7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=655}}</ref> On October 6, 1971 Morassa (Yazdi) Rawhani, a pioneer since February 1957, died. She had actively participated in the formation of two assemblies of Rabat and Sale. Her burial in the Bahá'í Cemetery at Rabat, was attended by a large number of believers of Morocco, the majority native believers; also in attendance was a representative from the Iranian Embassy in Rabat.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = In Memoriam|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1972 | number = 490 | page = 7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=991}}</ref> After four years of imprisonment Allal Rouhani has been released and on January 30, 1972, the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of North-West Africa held a luncheon attended by about sixty Bahá'ís and friends from all the local assemblies in the area. The Universal House of Justice was represented by Salim Nounou from France.<ref name="BN494" />

In 1975 the regional assembly of North West Africa was split into North and West separately. The regional National Assembly of Northern Africa included Egypt, Libya, Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco and Spanish Sahara.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Five new National Assemblies to form at Ridvan|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1975 | number = 526 | pages = 3–4| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=844}}</ref> In July 1975 the National Summer School of Spain in July which was at- tended by believers from Spain, Germany, France, and Morocco.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Around the world; Spain; Mr. Giachery speaks at Summer School|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1975 | volume = 52 | number = 8 | page = 20| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=69}}</ref> More than one parent/child conference was sponsored by the Bahá'ís of Morocco to mark the [[International Year of the Child]].<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Around the world; Morocco|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1980 | number = 592 |ISSN=0195-9212 | page = 17| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=227}}</ref> At the discussions on the draft of the ''Declaration on the Elimination of All Forms of Intolerance and of Discrimination Based on Religion or Belief'' at the ''Social, Cultural and Humanitarian Affairs Committee'' of the [[United Nations General Assembly]] there were several mentions of situation of the Bahá'ís in Iran—the Moroccan delegate made reference to "religious fanaticism" in a statement which also provoked a reply from Iran.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Dewlopments at the UN General Assembly|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1982 | number = 592 |ISSN=0195-9212 | pages = 4–6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=662}}</ref> Manuchihi Hizari, one of the first Bahá'ís in Morocco, left with his family in 1982 for the United States where he died in 2010.<ref>By which time he spelled his name as "Manouchehr Hezari"{{Cite news | last = Sanders | first = Joshunda | title = Austinite helped introduce Baha'i faith to Morocco | newspaper = The Austin Statesman | location = Austin Texas | date = June 26, 2010 | url = http://www.statesman.com/news/local/austinite-helped-introduce-bahai-faith-to-morocco-770167.html | accessdate = 2010-06-27 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100628065658/http://www.statesman.com/news/local/austinite-helped-introduce-bahai-faith-to-morocco-770167.html | archivedate = 2010-06-28 | deadurl = yes | df =  }}</ref> However persecutions occurred again in Morocco in 1983.<ref name="basic" /><ref name="IRF2001">{{cite web | author = U.S. State Department | title = 2001 Report on International Religious Freedom&nbsp;– Morocco | publisher = The Office of Electronic Information, Bureau of Public Affair | date = October 26, 2001 | url =https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2001/5655.htm | accessdate = 2010-06-07}}</ref> All Bahá'í meetings were prohibited. Published polemics in the 1970s and 1980s continued.<ref name="MacEoin">{{cite web | last = MacEoin | first = Denis |author2=William Collins | title = Anti-Baha'i Polemics | work = The Babi and Baha'i Religions: An Annotated Bibliography | publisher = Greenwood Press's ongoing series of Bibliographies and Indexes in Religious Studies | url = http://bahai-library.com/books/biblio/antibahai.polemic.html | accessdate = 2008-04-12|pages = entries # 132, 253, 353, 372, 411 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080515215132/http://bahai-library.com/books/biblio/antibahai.polemic.html| archivedate= 15 May 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In June 1984 a Bahá'í in Tetuan is arrested and sentenced to three years in prison for violating the ban on meetings.<ref name="basic" /> A response to these developments was to seek diplomatic redress emphasizing the non-partisan and obedience to government principles of the religion.<ref name="smith" />

Bahá'ís have more recently been denied passports and can practice their religion only in private.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhchr.ch/tbs/doc.nsf/(Symbol)/22916182b5219ed6c1256b58004f363e?Opendocument |title=Concluding observations of the Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination : Morocco |publisher=Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights |date=1994-04-03 |accessdate=2007-03-03 |author=Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination}} see paragraphs 215 and 220.</ref>

== Modern community ==

The events of 1962–3 are still considered a note on Moroccan politics.<ref name="WCMES" /> The 50th anniversary of the religion in Cameroon attracted some 560 Bahá'ís including visitors from a host of countries including Morocco in 2003.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = In Africa, four communities celebrate 50 years of progress| journal = One Country | volume = 15 | issue = 02 | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | location = Lilongwe, Malawi | date = July–September 2003 | url = http://www.onecountry.org/e152/e15211as_African_jubilee_story.htm | issn = | accessdate = 2010-06-07}}</ref> Moroccan Bahá'ís have managed to obtain acceptable national ID cards, avoiding the [[Egyptian identification card controversy]].<ref>{{Cite book | title = Prohibited Identities; State Interference with religious Freedom | volume = 19 | number = 07(e) | publisher = Human Rights Watch | date = November 2007 | page = 26 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6kfmoq7kb1wC&lpg=PA26&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=false | isbn = }}</ref> The religion is still considered heretical<ref>{{cite book | last = Taylor | first = Paul M. | authorlink = Paul M. Taylor | title = Freedom of religion: UN and European human rights law and practice | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2005 | page = 57 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=sS94Lw9eObIC&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=morocco+baha'i&source=bl&ots=0jbn-aKG4x&sig=XbW17wC1Pxo59qLutVd-igxHZ5k&hl=en&ei=vtPXTqOUH4fMgQfAma3lDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAzhu#v=onepage&q=morocco%20baha'i&f=false| isbn = 978-0-521-85649-2}}</ref> or some kind of non-religion religion according to Ayyad Ablal, a Moroccan sociologist.<ref>{{cite news | last = Al-Khanusi | first = Jamal |author2=Ayyad Ablal | title = The Baha’i Faith and Religious Pluralism in Morocco | newspaper = Al-Sabah Moroccan Newspaper | language = | publisher = The Muslim Network for Baha'i Rights | date = 18 April 2009 | url = http://www.bahairights.org/2009/06/02/the-bahaii-faith-and-religious-pluralism-in-morocco/ | accessdate = 2012-02-16}}</ref>

=== Demographics ===

1992 estimates by the US Department of State counted some 150-200 Bahá'ís<ref name="HRP-93" /> while 2001 through 2009 estimates mention the Bahá'í community, mostly in Rabat and Casablanca, at 350 to 400 persons.<ref name="IRF2001" /><ref name="IRF2009" /> However [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] and [[Wolfram Alpha]]<ref name="Wolfram"/> estimated 30,000 Bahá'ís in 2005 and 2010,<ref name="ARDA-BahaiNations"/> the third largest religion in the country.<ref name="ARDA-Morocco"/> The [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] quotes Census figures of 350 to 400 Bahá'í adherents.<ref name="ARDA-Morocco"/>

