{{distinguish|medical bag}} A '''medicine bag''' is usually a small pouch, worn by some [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas]], that contains sacred items. A personal medicine bag may contain objects that symbolize personal well-being and tribal identity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uCLXDQAAQBAJ|title=Listen to the Drum: Blackwolf Shares His Medicine|last=Jones|first=Blackwolf|last2=Jones|first2=Gina|publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]]|year=2010|isbn=9781592859733|location=[[Center City, Minnesota]]|pages=78}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Black Hawk: The Battle for the Heart of America|last=Trask|first=Kerry A.|publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company]]|year=2013|isbn=9781466860926|location=[[New York City]]|pages=113}}</ref> Traditionally, medicine bags are worn under the clothing.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_AIPAAAAYAAJ|title=The Story of Illinois and its People|last=Nida|first=William Lewis|publisher=O. P. Barnes|year=1913|isbn=|location=[[Chicago]]|pages=27}}</ref> Their contents are private, and often of a personal and religious nature.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peet|first=Stephen D.|date=1893|title=Craft Symbols and Religious Emblems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxwLAAAAYAAJ|journal=The American Antiquarian and Oriental Journal|volume=Volumes 15-16|pages=97}}</ref>
