'''William Bannerman''' (8 September 1822 – 24 December 1902) was a pioneering [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] minister in [[Otago]], New Zealand.
Bannerman was born in [[Kirkcaldy]], [[Fife]], Scotland in 1822, and received his tertiary education at the [[University of Edinburgh]] followed by the [[Edinburgh Theological Seminary|Free Church Theological College]]. He emigrated to New Zealand and arrived in [[Port Chalmers]] on the ''Stately'' on 5 February 1854. Bannerman settled at [[Puerua]], and he was responsible for the sparsely populated area between [[Waihola]] and [[Riverton, New Zealand|Riverton]]. Bannerman set up much of the administrative framework for the [[Presbyterian Church of Aotearoa New Zealand|Presbyterian church in New Zealand]]. He received the [[honorary degree]] [[Doctor of Divinity]] (DD) from the University of Edinburgh in March 1900.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=University intelligence|day_of_week=Saturday |date=3 March 1900 |page_number=8 |issue=36080| }}</ref> Bannerman died on 24 December 1902 in Dunedin.<ref name="DNZB William Bannerman">{{DNZB|Page|Dorothy |1b3|Bannerman, Jane and Bannerman, William|9 March 2015}}</ref>
Bannerman married [[Jane Bannerman|Jane Burns]] on 21 May 1856 at [[Dunedin]].
